# Hermetic principles for engineering

Seven framings, each useful for a different category of decision. Pick the one that fits.

## 1. Mentalism — build the mental model first

State the essence in one sentence. Name 5-7 entities. Map relationships. Validate. Then code.

When: starting new, joining unfamiliar codebase, architecture unclear.

## 2. Correspondence — patterns flow through levels

Domain → API → UI → DB. The pattern at the highest level appears at every level. Misalignment is a bug.

When: layers feel disconnected, API names don't match domain.

## 3. Vibration — ship to learn

Smallest shippable unit. Ship. Observe. Iterate. Maintain rhythm.

When: analysis paralysis, velocity stalled.

## 4. Polarity — both poles, name the cost

Every decision has tradeoffs. Name both. Pick the one serving the current goal. Set trigger to revisit.

When: a decision feels binary but both options are wrong.

## 5. Rhythm — phases are real

Feature spike → maintenance → feature spike. Don't fight the phase.

When: burning out, forcing work that isn't ready.

## 6. Cause and Effect — find the cause

Recurring symptoms mean unfixed causes. Trace upstream until the cause is named.

When: same bug class keeps appearing, recurring incidents.

## 7. Gender — generative + receptive

Every system needs both: it produces output, it receives input. Imbalance is broken.

When: a system doesn't take inputs (or ignores them), or produces output nobody uses.

## How to apply

- Stuck on architecture? Mentalism.
- Levels disconnected? Correspondence.
- Can't ship? Vibration.
- Decision false? Polarity.
- Burning out? Rhythm.
- Recurring bug? Cause and Effect.
- System dead? Gender.

Not all seven for every decision. Pick the one that fits the question.
